# QUERIES.log — Unit E (macro expansion), clean-room oracle interactions.
# Oracle = oracle/hs_oracle.sh <file.spthy> [extra args]; wraps the black-box HS
# tamarin-prover binary. Every entry: purpose -> what was observed (summary).
# All exact strings used in BEHAVIOR.md / tests trace to these observations.

[Q1]  hs_oracle.sh --help
      Purpose: discover output modes. Observed: flags --parse-only ("parse and
      pretty print as-is"), -m/--output-module {spthytyped,spthy,msr,...},
      --diff, -D defines, etc.

[Q2]  hs_oracle.sh issue777.spthy --parse-only  (and  --parse-only -m spthy)
      Purpose: does parse-only expand macros? Observed: NO. macros: block and
      the call Out( pk(~x) ) both preserved verbatim; no expansion.

[Q3]  hs_oracle.sh issue777.spthy   (default full close)
      Purpose: see expansion in closed theory. Observed: macros: block
      preserved; primary rule (modulo E) A keeps Out( pk(~x) ); the
      /* rule (modulo AC) A ... Out( 'g'^~x ) */ variant shows the EXPANSION
      pk(x)='g'^x -> 'g'^~x. Function signature does NOT list pk.

[Q4]  hs_oracle.sh MacroInLemmasAndRestrictions.spthy  (full close)
      Purpose: expansion in rules/lemmas/restrictions + nesting. Observed:
      rules keep macro call in modulo-E, expand in modulo-AC (A(m(x))->A(x),
      B(m2(x,y))->B(<x,y>)); restriction shows call then /* expanded formula:
      ...A( x )... */; lemma shows call then /* guarded formula ...A( x )...*/.
      Nested m(m3(x)) fully expands to x. Rule C (no macro) => trivial AC variant.

[Q5]  Byte-parity diff: issue777.spthy (macro) vs hand-written issue777_expanded
      Purpose: pin down exactly what is observably equal. Observed: outputs
      differ ONLY in (a) macros: line, (b) modulo-E rule call vs expanded term,
      (c) explicit modulo-AC block vs "trivial AC variant". The expanded term
      (macro AC-variant) is byte-identical to the hand-expanded primary rule.

[Q6]  Byte-parity diff: MacroInLemmasAndRestrictions vs lemmas_expanded
      Purpose: same, for lemmas/restrictions. Observed: same 3 scaffolding
      diffs; all expanded terms/formulas byte-identical.

[Q7]  probe capture.spthy: swap(x,y)=<x,y>, call swap(y,x)
      Purpose: substitution capture behaviour. Observed AC: Act( <y, x> ) =>
      SIMULTANEOUS (parallel) substitution, not sequential (no capture bug).

[Q8]  probe bodyref_fwd.spthy: macros: a(x)=b(x), b(x)=<x,x>   (forward ref)
      Purpose: can a body call a later macro? Observed: PARSE ERROR at b(x) in
      a's body. => body may reference only EARLIER macros.

[Q9]  probe bodyref_rev.spthy: macros: b(x)=<x,x>, a(x)=b(x)
      Purpose: body calls earlier macro. Observed: OK. Declaration prints
      a( x ) = b(x) (un-expanded); use-site AC = Act( <x, x> ) (transitive).

[Q10] probe zeroarg.spthy: macros: z()=~x, rule uses z()
      Purpose: nullary macro + free var in body. Observed: modulo-E Act( z )
      / Out( z ) (call printed w/o parens); AC Act( ~x ) / Out( ~x ). Body free
      var ~x captured by surrounding Fr(~x). z()=body substitutes body.

[Q11] probe arity_over.spthy: macros: m(x)=x, call m(a,b)
      Purpose: over-application of unary macro. Observed: NO error; parser packs
      args into a pair: modulo-E Act( m(<a, b>) ), AC Act( <a, b> ).

[Q12] probe arity_under.spthy: macros: m(x,y)=<x,y>, call m(a)  (under)
      Purpose: under-application. Observed: PARSE ERROR.

[Q13] probe dup.spthy: macros: m(x)=x, m(x)=<x,x>
      Purpose: duplicate macro name. Observed: ERROR "Conflicting name for macro m".

[Q14] probe redef_builtin.spthy: builtins: hashing + macros: h(x)=x
      Purpose: macro name == builtin. Observed: ERROR "Conflicting name for macro h".

[Q15] probe over_u3.spthy: macros: m(x)=<x,x>, call m(a,b,c)
      Purpose: unary macro, 3 args. Observed: args pack to <a,b,c>; AC =
      Act( <<a, b, c>, a, b, c> ) (= pair(<a,b,c>,<a,b,c>) w/ right-nest flatten
      print). Confirms parser packs excess args into a pair for arity-1.

[Q16] probe over_b3.spthy: macros: m2(x,y)=<x,y>, call m2(a,b,c)
      Purpose: binary macro, 3 args. Observed: PARSE ERROR. => arity>=2 needs
      EXACT arg count.

[Q17] probe under_b1.spthy: m2(x,y)=<x,y> call m2(a).  Observed: PARSE ERROR.

[Q18] probe chain3.spthy: macros: c(x)=<x,x>, b(x)=c(x), a(x)=b(x), call a(x)
      Purpose: multi-level transitive. Observed: AC Act( <x, x> ) (3-level).

[Q19] probe rec_self.spthy: macros: r(x)=r(x)
      Purpose: self recursion. Observed: PARSE ERROR (r not in scope in own
      body). => no recursion; expansion always terminates (macros form a DAG).

[Q20] probe rec_mutual.spthy: macros: a(x)=b(x), b(x)=a(x)
      Purpose: mutual recursion. Observed: PARSE ERROR (forward ref). => none.

[Q21] probe fun_collide.spthy: functions: f/1 + macros: f(x)=x
      Purpose: macro name == user function. Observed: ERROR "Conflicting name
      for macro f".

[Q22] probe shadow_formal.spthy: macros: m(x,x)=<x,x>
      Purpose: duplicate formal names. Observed: ERROR "m have two arguments
      with the same name" (Theory/Text/Parser/Macro.hs).

[Q23] probe letbind.spthy: macros: m(x)=<x,x>, rule let a=m(b) in ...Act(a)
      Purpose: macro inside let value. Observed: let inlined + macro expanded;
      AC Act( <b, b> ), Out( <b, b> ). (let-inlining is a separate pass.)

[Q24] probe unused.spthy: macros: used(x)=<x,x>, never(y)=h(y) (no hashing)
      Purpose: incidental. Observed: PARSE ERROR at h(y) — body cannot call an
      undeclared function.

[Q25] hs_oracle.sh issue753-3.spthy: macros: h(x)=x, NO builtins
      Purpose: macro named h without hashing. Observed: OK (no conflict); macro
      name conflicts only with ACTIVELY declared functions/builtins.

[Q26] probe diffmacro.spthy --diff: macros: m(x)=<x,x>, Out(diff(x,m(x)))
      Purpose: expansion under diff. Observed: modulo-E keeps diff(x, m(x));
      left proj Out( x ), right proj Out( <x, x> ); Act(m(x)) => <x,x> both
      sides. Macro expands inside diff() term; diff-projection is separate.

[Q27] probe sortmatch.spthy: macros: m(x)=~x, n(x)=x; M(m(a)), N(n(~b))
      Purpose: is formal matching sort-sensitive? Observed: AC M( ~x ) (formal
      x [untagged] does NOT match body ~x [fresh]; ~x left free -> unbound-var
      warning) and N( ~b ) (x matches x, arg ~b substituted). => substitution
      matches formal-to-body-var by full identity incl. SORT. Unmatched formal's
      argument is simply dropped.

[Q28] probe sortmatch2.spthy: macros: p(x)=$x, call p(a).  Observed: AC P( $x )
      — $x [pub] does not match formal x [untagged] either.

[Q29] probe procmacro.spthy (parse-only + full): macro in a Sapic process
      Purpose: expansion inside processes. Observed: process translates to rules;
      modulo-AC of the translated rules show A( <y, y> ), Out( <y,y> ) => macros
      expand inside processes too.

[Q30] MacroWithRestrictionCRxor.spthy (full): hashedxor(x,y,z)=h(x XOR y XOR z)
      Purpose: xor-macro rendering. Observed: modulo-E keeps hashedxor(...);
      expanded form h(x XOR y XOR z), but AC-variant machinery abstracts it to
      h(z) with a variant table. Confounded by AC variants -> NOT used as a
      strict byte-parity fixture (structural expansion is still App("h",[Xor..])).

[Q31] byteparity.sh on 6 fixture pairs (capture, chain3, over_u3, sortmatch,
      issue777, lemmas). Purpose: automated byte-parity of expanded content
      (macro theory vs hand-expanded equivalent). Result: ALL OK — expanded
      content byte-identical after stripping the 3 known scaffolding categories.

# ---- Round 4: bare nullary uses [GAP1], acc-lemma [GAP2] & case-test [GAP3]
#      formulas, and preservation of the macros: block. ----------------------

[Q32] probes/bare_nullary.spthy vs probes/paren_nullary.spthy (full close);
      probes/bare_prem.spthy; probes/bare_inarg.spthy; probes/bare_msgsort.spthy.
      macros: konst() = h('k').
      Purpose: how is a 0-ary macro used WITHOUT parentheses treated?
      Observed: a bare `konst` is treated IDENTICALLY to `konst()` — modulo-E
      keeps the bare name `A( konst )`, modulo-AC shows `A( h('k') )`. Holds in
      premise, action AND conclusion positions (bare_prem: In( konst ) => In(
      h('k') )), and nested inside functions (bare_inarg: h(konst)/sign(konst,x)
      => h('k')/sign('k',x)). A macro-name use cannot be sort-annotated:
      `konst:msg` is a parse error ("unexpected ':'"). => a bare nullary use is
      always the plain (untagged) form and DOES expand.

[Q33] probes/bare_chain.spthy: macros: base()=h('k'), wrap()=h(base); bare wrap.
      Purpose: does a bare nullary use inside a macro body expand?
      Observed: declaration prints wrap( ) = h(base) (un-expanded body); use of
      bare `wrap` => modulo-AC A( h(h('k')) ). => bare nullary uses expand
      transitively through bodies, exactly like parenthesised calls.

[Q34] probes/bare_sorts.spthy: macros: konst()=h('k'); uses ~konst and $konst.
      Purpose: does a fresh/pub-sorted bare name resolve to the nullary macro?
      Observed: NO. ~konst and $konst stay ordinary variables (modulo-AC
      A( ~konst ), B( $konst.1 )) and raise unbound-variable / sort-mismatch
      warnings. => nullary-name resolution is UNTAGGED-sort only (consistent
      with the sort-identity rule [Q27,Q28]).

[Q35] probes/bare_nonnullary.spthy: macros: m(x)=<x,x>; bare `m` (no args).
      Purpose: does a bare name equal to an arity>=1 macro resolve?
      Observed: NO. `A( m )` is left as-is; `m` is an unbound variable (trivial
      AC variant, unbound-variable warning). => only a NULLARY macro is resolved
      from a bare name.

[Q36] probes/formal_vs_nullary.spthy: macros: base()=h('k'), f(base)=<base,base>;
      call f(a).  Purpose: when a formal name equals an existing nullary macro,
      which wins inside the body? Observed: modulo-AC A( <h('k'), h('k')> ) — the
      NULLARY MACRO wins; the formal `base` and the argument `a` are dropped.
      => a nullary macro reserves its name against a same-named formal; a body's
      bare occurrences resolve to the macro before formal binding.

[Q37] every full-close capture (e.g. captures/bare_nullary_macro.out,
      captures/example_issue777.out, probes/acc_macro full close).
      Purpose: does the reference retain the macros: block after processing?
      Observed: YES — the pretty output always reprints `macros: <name>( args )
      = <body>, ...` with the ORIGINAL (un-expanded) bodies, regardless of how
      the uses are expanded elsewhere. => the declaration block is preserved in
      place; `expand` keeps the Macros items unchanged.

[Q38] fixtures/acclemma_macro.spthy vs acclemma_expanded.spthy; acc_both_macro
      vs acc_both_expanded (full accountability close via formula_parity.sh).
      macro `af(x)=h(x)` used in a `... accounts for "..."` formula.
      Purpose: does the macro stage expand acc-lemma formulas, and at what
      stage? Observed: --parse-only preserves the call (Unequal( af(sid) )). On
      close the accountability lemma is translated into generated lemmas whose
      PRIMARY formulas still show the call (Unequal( af(sid) )) and whose
      `/* guarded formula characterizing ... */` shows the EXPANDED form
      (Unequal( h(sid) )). formula_parity.sh: the macro theory's guarded content
      is byte-identical to the hand-inlined equivalent's. => macros ARE expanded
      in acc-lemma formulas, visible at the guarded/processing stage (same
      pattern as ordinary lemmas [Q4]).

[Q39] fixtures/casetest_macro.spthy vs casetest_expanded.spthy; acc_both pair.
      macro `ct(x)=h(x)` used in a `test <name>: "..."` case-test formula.
      Purpose: same probe for case tests. Observed: --parse-only preserves
      Blame( ct(sid), x ). On close the case test feeds the generated
      `predicate: Blamed(x) <=> ... Blame( ct(sid), x ) ...` (call kept) and the
      generated lemmas' guarded formulas show Blame( h(sid), x ) (expanded).
      formula_parity.sh: guarded content byte-identical to the hand-inlined
      equivalent. => macros ARE expanded in case-test formulas at the
      guarded/processing stage.

[Q40] run_tests.sh (round 4): 21 cargo direct-expansion tests + 7 byteparity
      rule fixtures (incl. bare_nullary) + 4 formula_parity fixtures (lemmas,
      casetest, acclemma, acc_both). Result: ALL PASS.

# Note: the byteparity.sh env-stripping harness cannot exercise accountability
# theories (its reduced env lacks a UTF-8 locale, so the reference aborts on the
# ∀/∃ logic glyphs before generating lemmas). formula_parity.sh runs the oracle
# with a UTF-8 locale and compares only the guarded/expanded-formula blocks, so
# it is the harness of record for the acc-lemma / case-test gaps.

# ---- Round 5: reconcile the consumer's STAGED-MODE (parse-stage) contract ----
#      with fresh parse-stage observations. Given as an INTERFACE contract:
#      (a) acc-lemma & case-test formulas left UNTOUCHED (later stage owns them);
#      (b) rules exist only in their PRIMARY form (no derived variant/left-right).

[Q41] fixtures/acc_both_macro.spthy --parse-only
      Purpose: reconcile interop (a) — is the parse-stage view of an acc-lemma /
      case-test the un-expanded call? Observed: the case-test prints
      `test blamed: "∃ sid #i. Blame( mtest(sid), x ) @ #i"` and the acc-lemma
      prints `blamed accounts for "¬(∃ sid #i. Unequal( mfor(sid) ) @ #i)"` — both
      macro CALLS preserved verbatim, NO expansion at parse stage (consistent with
      [Q2,Q38,Q39]). => the parse-stage view leaves acc-lemma & case-test formulas
      untouched; the consumer's staged expand() must too (a later stage expands
      them, as the guarded forms at close showed [Q38,Q39]).

[Q42] examples/regression/trace/issue777.spthy --parse-only;
      examples/features/macros/MacroInLemmasAndRestrictions.spthy --parse-only
      Purpose: reconcile interop (b) — in what form do rules exist at parse stage?
      Observed: each rule prints ONLY as `rule (modulo E) <name>:` with its primary
      premises/actions/conclusions (macro CALL preserved: `Out( pk(~x) )`,
      `A( m(x) )`, `B( m2(x, y) )`). NO `(modulo AC)` variant block, NO left/right
      diff projection is present at parse stage. => at the consumer's stage a rule
      exists only in its primary form; there are no derived/variant rule forms to
      recurse into. (The `(modulo AC)` variant / diff projections that DO show the
      expansion [Q3,Q4,Q26] appear only at close — the later stage the consumer's
      full-close entry, `expand`, still serves.)

# Staged mode ([Q41,Q42]) is the consumer's parse-stage view. Note the reference's
# --parse-only is fully lazy (expands NOTHING, incl. ordinary lemmas' guarded
# forms [Q2]); the consumer's contract is NOT that — its staged expand eagerly
# expands ordinary lemmas/restrictions/primary-rules (and bare-nullary uses), and
# ONLY carves out acc-lemma/case-test formulas [Q41] and derived rule forms [Q42].
# `expand_staged` implements that contract; `expand` remains the full-close entry.
